[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] In computer science, in particular in knowledge representation and reasoning and metalogic, the area of **automated reasoning** is dedicated to understanding different aspects of reasoning.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] The study of automated reasoning helps produce computer programs that allow computers to reason completely, or nearly completely, automatically.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] Although automated reasoning is considered a sub-field of artificial intelligence, it also has connections with theoretical computer science and philosophy.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] The most developed subareas of automated reasoning are automated theorem proving (and the less automated but more pragmatic subfield of interactive theorem proving) and automated proof checking (viewed as guaranteed correct reasoning under fixed assumptions).
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] Extensive work has also been done in reasoning by analogy using induction and abduction.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] Other important topics include reasoning under uncertainty and non-monotonic reasoning.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] An important part of the uncertainty field is that of argumentation, where further constraints of minimality and consistency are applied on top of the more standard automated deduction.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] John Pollock's OSCAR system is an example of an automated argumentation system that is more specific than being just an automated theorem prover.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] Tools and techniques of automated reasoning include the classical logics and calculi, fuzzy logic, Bayesian inference, reasoning with maximal entropy and many less formal *ad hoc* techniques.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] The development of formal logic played a big role in the field of automated reasoning, which itself led to the development of artificial intelligence.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] A formal proof is a proof in which every logical inference has been checked back to the fundamental axioms of mathematics.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] All the intermediate logical steps are supplied, without exception.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] No appeal is made to intuition, even if the translation from intuition to logic is routine.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] Thus, a formal proof is less intuitive and less susceptible to logical errors.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] Some consider the Cornell Summer meeting of 1957, which brought together many logicians and computer scientists, as the origin of automated reasoning, or automated deduction.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] Others say that it began before that with the 1955 Logic Theorist program of Newell, Shaw and Simon, or with Martin Davis’ 1954 implementation of Presburger's decision procedure (which proved that the sum of two even numbers is even).
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] Automated reasoning, although a significant and popular area of research, went through an "AI winter" in the eighties and early nineties.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] The field subsequently revived, however.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] For example, in 2005, Microsoft started using verification technology in many of their internal projects and is planning to include a logical specification and checking language in their 2012 version of Visual C.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] Principia Mathematica was a milestone work in formal logic written by Alfred North Whitehead and Bertrand Russell.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] Its purpose was to derive all or some of the mathematical expressions, in terms of symbolic logic.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] Principia Mathematica was initially published in three volumes in 1910, 1912 and 1913.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] It succeeded The Principles of Mathematics, a 1903 book by Bertrand Russell, in which Russell had presented his famous paradox and argued his thesis that mathematics and logic are identical.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] Logic Theorist (LT) was the first ever program developed in 1956 by Allen Newell, Cliff Shaw and Herbert A.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] Simon to "mimic human reasoning" in proving theorems and was demonstrated on fifty-two theorems from chapter two of Principia Mathematica, proving thirty-eight of them.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] In addition to proving the theorems, the program found a proof for one of the theorems that was more elegant than the one provided by Whitehead and Russell.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] "There are now in the world machines that think, that learn and that create.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] was influenced by John McCarthy and Woody Bledsoe.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] 2. the reliance on a principle of definition for total recursive functions.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] 3. the extensive use of rewriting and "symbolic evaluation".
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] 4. an induction heuristic based the failure of symbolic evaluation.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] is designed to have a simple and clean logical foundation and an uncluttered implementation.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] It is essentially another proof assistant for classical higher order logic.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] Properties, programs and proofs are formalized in the same language called the Calculus of Inductive Constructions (CIC).
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] Automated reasoning has been most commonly used to build automated theorem provers.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] Oftentimes, however, theorem provers require some human guidance to be effective and so more generally qualify as proof assistants.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] In some cases such provers have come up with new approaches to proving a theorem.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] Logic Theorist is a good example of this.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] The program came up with a proof for one of the theorems in Principia Mathematica that was more efficient (requiring fewer steps) than the proof provided by Whitehead and Russell.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] Automated reasoning programs are being applied to solve a growing number of problems in formal logic, mathematics and computer science, logic programming, software and hardware verification, circuit design, and many others.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] The TPTP (Sutcliffe and Suttner 1998) is a library of such problems that is updated on a regular basis.
[src:knuth-bendix/automated-reasoning] There is also a competition among automated theorem provers held regularly at the CADE conference (Pelletier, Sutcliffe and Suttner 2002); the problems for the competition are selected from the TPTP library.
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] In the theory of multivariate polynomials, **Buchberger's algorithm** is a method for transforming a given set of polynomials into a Gröbner basis, which is another set of polynomials that have the same common zeros and are more convenient for extracting information on these common zeros.
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] It was introduced by Bruno Buchberger simultaneously with the definition of Gröbner bases.
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] The Euclidean algorithm for computing the polynomial greatest common divisor is a special case of Buchberger's algorithm restricted to polynomials of a single variable.
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] Gaussian elimination of a system of linear equations is another special case where the degree of all polynomials equals one.
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] For other Gröbner basis algorithms, see Gröbner basis § Algorithms and implementations.
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] For every *fi*, *fj* in *G*, denote by *gi* the leading term of *fi* with respect to the given monomial ordering, and by *aij* the least common multiple of *gi* and *gj*.
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] Choose two polynomials in *G* and let *S**ij* = ⁠*a**ij*/ *g**i*⁠ *f**i* − ⁠*a**ij*/ *g**j*⁠ *f**j* *(The leading terms here will cancel by construction)*.
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] Reduce *S**ij*, with the multivariate division algorithm relative to the set *G* until the result is not further reducible.
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] If the result is non-zero, add it to *G*.
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] Repeat steps 2–4 until all possible pairs are considered, including those involving the new polynomials added in step 4.
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] The polynomial *S**ij* is commonly referred to as the *S*-polynomial, where *S* refers to *subtraction* (Buchberger) or *syzygy* (others).
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] The pair of polynomials with which it is associated is commonly referred to as critical pair.
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] There are many ways to improve this algorithm beyond what has been stated above.
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] For example, all the new elements of *F* can be reduced relative to each other before adding them.
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] If the leading terms of *fi* and *fj* share no variables in common, then *Sij* will *always* reduce to 0 (if using only fi and fj for reduction), so it needn't be calculated at all.
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] The algorithm terminates because it is consistently increasing the size of the monomial ideal generated by the leading terms of our set *F*, and Dickson's lemma (or the Hilbert basis theorem) guarantees that any such ascending chain must eventually become constant.
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] The computational complexity of Buchberger's algorithm is very difficult to estimate, because of the number of choices that may dramatically change the computation time.
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] where *n* is the number of variables, and *d* the maximal total degree of the input polynomials.
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] This allows, in theory, to use linear algebra over the vector space of the polynomials of degree bounded by this value, for getting an algorithm of complexity $d^{2^{n+o(1)}}$ .
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] and the above upper bound of complexity is optimal.
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] Nevertheless, such examples are extremely rare.
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] Since its discovery, many variants of Buchberger's have been introduced to improve its efficiency.
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] Faugère's F4 and F5 algorithms are presently the most efficient algorithms for computing Gröbner bases, and allow to compute routinely Gröbner bases consisting of several hundreds of polynomials, having each several hundreds of terms and coefficients of several hundreds of digits.
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] At least one implementation of Buchberger’s algorithm has been proved correct within the proof assistant Rocq (formerly named Coq).
[src:knuth-bendix/buchberger-s-algorithm] In the SymPy library for Python, the (improved) Buchberger algorithm is implemented as `sympy.polys.polytools.groebner()`.
[src:knuth-bendix/equational-logic] First-order **equational logic** consists of quantifier-free terms of ordinary first-order logic, with equality as the only predicate symbol.
[src:knuth-bendix/equational-logic] The model theory of this logic was developed into universal algebra by Birkhoff, Grätzer, and Cohn.
[src:knuth-bendix/equational-logic] It was later made into a branch of category theory by Lawvere ("algebraic theories").
[src:knuth-bendix/equational-logic] The terms of equational logic are built up from variables and constants using function symbols (or operations).
[src:knuth-bendix/equational-logic] Here are the four inference rules of logic. ${\textstyle P[x:=E]}$ denotes textual substitution of expression ${\textstyle E}$ for variable ${\textstyle x}$ in expression ${\textstyle P}$ .
[src:knuth-bendix/equational-logic] Next, ${\textstyle b=c}$ denotes equality, for ${\textstyle b}$ and ${\textstyle c}$ of the same type, while ${\textstyle b\equiv c}$ , or equivalence, is defined only for ${\textstyle b}$ and ${\textstyle c}$ of type boolean.
[src:knuth-bendix/equational-logic] For ${\textstyle b}$ and ${\textstyle c}$ of type boolean, ${\textstyle b=c}$ and ${\textstyle b\equiv c}$ have the same meaning.
[src:knuth-bendix/equational-logic] We explain how the four inference rules are used in proofs, using the proof of ${\textstyle \lnot p\equiv p\equiv \bot }$ .
[src:knuth-bendix/equational-logic] The logic symbols ${\textstyle \top }$ and ${\textstyle \bot }$ indicate "true" and "false," respectively, and ${\textstyle \lnot }$ indicates "not." The theorem numbers refer to theorems of *A Logical Approach to Discrete Math*.
[src:knuth-bendix/equational-logic] is the conclusion of Leibniz, and its premise ${\textstyle \lnot (p\equiv p)\equiv \lnot p\equiv p}$ is given on line ${\textstyle (1)}$ .
[src:knuth-bendix/equational-logic] In the same way, the equality on lines ${\textstyle (2)}$ – ${\textstyle (4)}$ are substantiated using Leibniz.
[src:knuth-bendix/equational-logic] The "hint" on line ${\textstyle (1)}$ is supposed to give a premise of Leibniz, showing what substitution of equals for equals is being used.
[src:knuth-bendix/equational-logic] This premise is theorem ${\textstyle (3.9)}$ with the substitution ${\textstyle p:=q}$ , i.e.
[src:knuth-bendix/equational-logic] This shows how inference rule Substitution is used within hints.
[src:knuth-bendix/equational-logic] Finally, note that line ${\textstyle (4)}$ , ${\textstyle \lnot \top \equiv \bot }$ , is a theorem, as indicated by the hint to its right.
[src:knuth-bendix/equational-logic] Hence, by inference rule Equanimity, we conclude that line ${\textstyle (0)}$ is also a theorem.
[src:knuth-bendix/equational-logic] And ${\textstyle (0)}$ is what we wanted to prove.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] The **Knuth–Bendix completion algorithm** (named after Donald Knuth and Peter Bendix) is a semi-decision algorithm for transforming a set of equations (over terms) into a confluent term rewriting system.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] When the algorithm succeeds, it effectively solves the word problem for the specified algebra.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Buchberger's algorithm for computing Gröbner bases is a very similar algorithm.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Although developed independently, it may also be seen as the instantiation of Knuth–Bendix algorithm in the theory of polynomial rings.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] For a set *E* of equations, its **deductive closure** (⁎⟷*E*) is the set of all equations that can be derived by applying equations from *E* in any order.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Formally, *E* is considered a binary relation, (⟶*E*) is its rewrite closure, and (⁎⟷*E*) is the equivalence closure of (⟶*E*).
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] For a set *R* of rewrite rules, its **deductive closure** (⁎⟶*R* ∘ ⁎⟵*R*) is the set of all equations that can be confirmed by applying rules from *R* left-to-right to both sides until they are literally equal.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Formally, *R* is again viewed as a binary relation, (⟶*R*) is its rewrite closure, (⟵*R*) is its converse, and (⁎⟶*R* ∘ ⁎⟵*R*) is the relation composition of their reflexive transitive closures (⁎⟶*R* and ⁎⟵*R*).
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] demonstrates that *a*−1⋅(*a*⋅*b*) ⁎⟷*E* *b* is a member of *E'*s deductive closure.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] However, there is no way to derive *a*−1⋅(*a*⋅*b*) ⁎⟶*R*∘⁎⟵*R* *b* similar to above, since a right-to-left application of the rule (*x*⋅*y*)⋅*z* → *x*⋅(*y*⋅*z*) is not allowed.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] The Knuth–Bendix algorithm takes a set *E* of equations between terms, and a reduction ordering (>) on the set of all terms, and attempts to construct a confluent and terminating term rewriting system *R* that has the same deductive closure as *E*.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] While proving consequences from *E* often requires human intuition, proving consequences from *R* does not.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] For more details, see Confluence (abstract rewriting)#Motivating examples, which gives an example proof from group theory, performed both using *E* and using *R*.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] The following example run, obtained from the E theorem prover, computes a completion of the (additive) group axioms as in Knuth, Bendix (1970).
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] It starts with the three initial equations for the group (neutral element 0, inverse elements, associativity), using `f(X,Y)` for *X*+*Y*, and `i(X)` for −*X*.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] The 10 starred equations turn out to constitute the resulting convergent rewrite system.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] "pm" is short for "paramodulation", implementing *deduce*.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Critical pair computation is an instance of paramodulation for equational unit clauses.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] "rw" is rewriting, implementing *compose*, *collapse*, and *simplify*.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Orienting of equations is done implicitly and not recorded.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] See also Word problem (mathematics) for another presentation of this example.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] An important case in computational group theory is string rewriting systems which can be used to give canonical labels to elements or cosets of a finitely presented group as products of the generators.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] This special case is the focus of this section.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] The critical pair lemma states that a term rewriting system is locally confluent (or weakly confluent) if and only if all its critical pairs are convergent.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Furthermore, we have Newman's lemma which states that if an (abstract) rewriting system is strongly normalizing and weakly confluent, then the rewriting system is confluent.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] So, if we can add rules to the term rewriting system in order to force all critical pairs to be convergent while maintaining the strong normalizing property, then this will force the resultant rewriting system to be confluent.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Consider a finitely presented monoid $M=\langle X\mid R\rangle$ where X is a finite set of generators and R is a set of defining relations on X.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Let X* be the set of all words in X (i.e. the free monoid generated by X).
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Since the relations R generate an equivalence relation on X*, one can consider elements of M to be the equivalence classes of X* under R.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] For each class *{w1, w2, ... }* it is desirable to choose a standard representative *wk*.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] This representative is called the **canonical** or **normal form** for each word *wk* in the class.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] If there is a computable method to determine for each *wk* its normal form *wi* then the word problem is easily solved.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] A confluent rewriting system allows one to do precisely this.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Although the choice of a canonical form can theoretically be made in an arbitrary fashion this approach is generally not computable.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] (Consider that an equivalence relation on a language can produce an infinite number of infinite classes.) If the language is well-ordered then the order < gives a consistent method for defining minimal representatives, however computing these representatives may still not be possible.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] This property is called **translation invariance**.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] An order that is both translation-invariant and a well-order is called a **reduction order**.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] From the presentation of the monoid it is possible to define a rewriting system given by the relations R.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] If A x B is in R then either A < B in which case B → A is a rule in the rewriting system, otherwise A > B and A → B.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Since < is a reduction order a given word W can be reduced W > W_1 > ... > W_n where W_n is irreducible under the rewriting system.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] However, depending on the rules that are applied at each Wi → Wi+1 it is possible to end up with two different irreducible reductions Wn ≠ W'm of W.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] However, if the rewriting system given by the relations is converted to a confluent rewriting system via the Knuth–Bendix algorithm, then all reductions are guaranteed to produce the same irreducible word, namely the normal form for that word.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Suppose we are given a presentation $\langle X\mid R\rangle$ , where X is a set of generators and R is a set of relations giving the rewriting system.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Suppose further that we have a reduction ordering < among the words generated by X (e.g., shortlex order).
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Thus we begin with the set of reductions $P_{i}\rightarrow Q_{i}$ .
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] First, if any relation $P_{i}=Q_{i}$ can be reduced, replace $P_{i}$ and $Q_{i}$ with the reductions.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Next, we add more reductions (that is, rewriting rules) to eliminate possible exceptions of confluence.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Suppose that $P_{i}$ and $P_{j}$ overlap.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Case 2: either $P_{i}$ is completely contained in (surrounded by) $P_{j}$ , or vice versa.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] In the former case, we can write $P_{i}=B$ and $P_{j}=ABC$ ; in the latter case, $P_{i}=ABC$ and $P_{j}=B$ .
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Reduce the word $ABC$ using $P_{i}$ first, then using $P_{j}$ first.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] If $r_{1}\neq r_{2}$ , then we have an instance where confluence could fail.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] After adding a rule to R , remove any rules in R that might have reducible left sides (after checking if such rules have critical pairs with other rules).
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Repeat the procedure until all overlapping left sides have been checked.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] This is an infinite monoid but nevertheless, the Knuth–Bendix algorithm is able to solve the word problem.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] A suffix of $x^{3}$ (namely x ) is a prefix of $(xy)^{3}=xyxyxy$ , so consider the word $x^{3}yxyxy$ .
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Reducing using (**1**), we get $yxyxy$ .
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Both of these rules obsolete (**3**), so we remove it.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] These obsolete rules (**4**) and (**5**), so we remove them.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Checking the overlaps of these rules, we find no potential failures of confluence.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] Therefore, we have a confluent rewriting system, and the algorithm terminates successfully.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] The order of the generators may crucially affect whether the Knuth–Bendix completion terminates.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] The Knuth–Bendix completion with respect to lexicographic order $x<x^{-1}<y<y^{-1}$ finishes with a convergent system, however considering the length-lexicographic order $x<y<x^{-1}<y^{-1}$ it does not finish for there are no finite convergent systems compatible with this latter order.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] If Knuth–Bendix does not succeed, it will either run forever and produce successive approximations to an infinite complete system, or fail when it encounters an unorientable equation (i.e. an equation that it cannot turn into a rewrite rule).
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] An enhanced version will not fail on unorientable equations and produces a ground confluent system, providing a semi-algorithm for the word problem.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] The notion of logged rewriting discussed in the paper by Heyworth and Wensley listed below allows some recording or logging of the rewriting process as it proceeds.
[src:knuth-bendix/knuth-bendix-completion-algorithm] This is useful for computing identities among relations for presentations of groups.
[src:knuth-bendix/path-ordering-term-rewriting] where (.>) is a user-given total precedence order on the set of all function symbols.
[src:knuth-bendix/path-ordering-term-rewriting] Intuitively, a term *f*(...) is bigger than any term *g*(...) built from terms *s**i* smaller than *f*(...) using a lower-precedence root symbol *g*.
[src:knuth-bendix/path-ordering-term-rewriting] In particular, by structural induction, a term *f*(...) is bigger than any term containing only symbols smaller than *f*.
[src:knuth-bendix/path-ordering-term-rewriting] A path ordering is often used as reduction ordering in term rewriting, in particular in the Knuth–Bendix completion algorithm.
[src:knuth-bendix/path-ordering-term-rewriting] As an example, a term rewriting system for "multiplying out" mathematical expressions could contain a rule *x**(*y*+*z*) → (*x***y*) + (*x***z*).
[src:knuth-bendix/path-ordering-term-rewriting] In order to prove termination, a reduction ordering (>) must be found with respect to which the term *x**(*y*+*z*) is greater than the term (*x***y*)+(*x***z*).
[src:knuth-bendix/path-ordering-term-rewriting] This is not trivial, since the former term contains both fewer function symbols and fewer variables than the latter.
[src:knuth-bendix/path-ordering-term-rewriting] There may also be systems for certain general recursive functions, for example a system for the Ackermann function may contain the rule A(*a*+, *b*+) → A(*a*, A(*a*+, *b*)), where *b*+ denotes the successor of *b*.
[src:knuth-bendix/path-ordering-term-rewriting] Given two terms *s* and *t*, with a root symbol *f* and *g*, respectively, to decide their relation their root symbols are compared first.
[src:knuth-bendix/path-ordering-term-rewriting] Dershowitz, Okada (1988) list more variants, and relate them to Ackermann's system of ordinal notations.
[src:knuth-bendix/path-ordering-term-rewriting] In particular, an upper bound given on the order types of recursive path orderings with *n* function symbols is φ(*n*,0), using Veblen's function for large countable ordinals.
[src:knuth-bendix/path-ordering-term-rewriting] The multiset extension, mapping (>) above to (>>) above is one example of an order functional: (>>)=*O*(>).
[src:knuth-bendix/path-ordering-term-rewriting] Another order functional is the lexicographic extension, leading to the **lexicographic path ordering**.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] In computational mathematics, a **word problem** is the problem of deciding whether two given expressions are equivalent with respect to a set of rewriting identities.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] A prototypical example is the word problem for groups, but there are many other instances as well.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] Some deep results of computational theory concern the undecidability of this question in many important cases.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] In computer algebra one often wishes to encode mathematical expressions using an expression tree.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] But there are often multiple equivalent expression trees.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The question naturally arises of whether there is an algorithm which, given as input two expressions, decides whether they represent the same element.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] Such an algorithm is called a *solution to the word problem*.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The most direct solution to a word problem takes the form of a normal form theorem and algorithm that maps every element in an equivalence class of expressions to a single encoding known as the normal form - the word problem is then solved by comparing these normal forms via syntactic equality.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] But not all solutions to the word problem use a normal form theorem - there are algebraic properties that indirectly imply the existence of an algorithm.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] One of the most deeply studied cases of the word problem is in the theory of semigroups and groups.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The accessibility problem for string rewriting systems (semi-Thue systems or semigroups) can be stated as follows: Given a semi-Thue system $T:=(\Sigma ,R)$ and two words (strings) $u,v\in \Sigma ^{*}$ , can u be transformed into v by applying rules from R ?
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] Note that the rewriting here is one-way.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The word problem is the accessibility problem for symmetric rewrite relations, i.e.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The accessibility and word problems are undecidable, i.e. there is no general algorithm for solving this problem.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] This even holds if we limit the systems to have finite presentations, i.e. a finite set of symbols and a finite set of relations on those symbols.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] Even the word problem restricted to ground terms is not decidable for certain finitely presented semigroups.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] Given a presentation $\langle S\mid {\mathcal {R}}\rangle$ for a group *G*, the word problem is the algorithmic problem of deciding, given as input two words in *S*, whether they represent the same element of *G*.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The word problem is one of three algorithmic problems for groups proposed by Max Dehn in 1911.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] It was shown by Pyotr Novikov in 1955 that there exists a finitely presented group *G* such that the word problem for *G* is undecidable.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] One of the earliest proofs that a word problem is undecidable was for combinatory logic: when are two strings of combinators equivalent?
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] Because combinators encode all possible Turing machines, and the equivalence of two Turing machines is undecidable, it follows that the equivalence of two strings of combinators is undecidable.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] Likewise, one has essentially the same problem in (untyped) lambda calculus: given two distinct lambda expressions, there is no algorithm that can discern whether they are equivalent or not; equivalence is undecidable.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] For several typed variants of the lambda calculus, equivalence is decidable by comparison of normal forms.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The word problem for an abstract rewriting system (ARS) is quite succinct: given objects *x* and *y* are they equivalent under ${\stackrel {*}{\leftrightarrow }}$ ?
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The word problem for an ARS is undecidable in general.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The Knuth-Bendix completion algorithm can be used to transform a set of equations into a convergent term rewriting system.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] In universal algebra one studies algebraic structures consisting of a generating set *A*, a collection of operations on *A* of finite arity, and a finite set of identities that these operations must satisfy.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The word problem for an algebra is then to determine, given two expressions (words) involving the generators and operations, whether they represent the same element of the algebra modulo the identities.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The word problems for groups and semigroups can be phrased as word problems for algebras.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The word problem on free Heyting algebras is difficult.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The only known results are that the free Heyting algebra on one generator is infinite, and that the free complete Heyting algebra on one generator exists (and has one more element than the free Heyting algebra).
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The word problem on free lattices and more generally free bounded lattices has a decidable solution.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] Bounded lattices are algebraic structures with the two binary operations ∨ and ∧ and the two constants (nullary operations) 0 and 1.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The set of all well-formed expressions that can be formulated using these operations on elements from a given set of generators *X* will be called **W**(*X*).
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] This set of words contains many expressions that turn out to denote equal values in every lattice.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] For example, if *a* is some element of *X*, then *a* ∨ 1 = 1 and *a* ∧ 1 = *a*.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The word problem for free bounded lattices is the problem of determining which of these elements of **W**(*X*) denote the same element in the free bounded lattice *FX*, and hence in every bounded lattice.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The word problem may be resolved as follows.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] This defines a preorder ≤~ on **W**(*X*), so an equivalence relation can be defined by *w* ~ *v* when *w* ≤~ *v* and *v* ≤~ *w*.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] One may then show that the partially ordered quotient set **W**(*X*)/~ is the free bounded lattice *FX*.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The equivalence classes of **W**(*X*)/~ are the sets of all words *w* and *v* with *w* ≤~ *v* and *v* ≤~ *w*.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] Two well-formed words *v* and *w* in **W**(*X*) denote the same value in every bounded lattice if and only if *w* ≤~ *v* and *v* ≤~ *w*; the latter conditions can be effectively decided using the above inductive definition.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The table shows an example computation to show that the words *x*∧*z* and *x*∧*z*∧(*x*∨*y*) denote the same value in every bounded lattice.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The case of lattices that are not bounded is treated similarly, omitting rules 2 and 3 in the above construction of ≤~.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] Bläsius and Bürckert demonstrate the Knuth–Bendix algorithm on an axiom set for groups.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The algorithm yields a confluent and noetherian term rewrite system that transforms every term into a unique normal form.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The rewrite rules are numbered incontiguous since some rules became redundant and were deleted during the algorithm run.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] The equality of two terms follows from the axioms if and only if both terms are transformed into literally the same normal form term.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] 1 ; therefore both terms are equal in every group.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] As another example, the term $1\cdot (a\cdot b)$ and $b\cdot (1\cdot a)$ has the normal form $a\cdot b$ and $b\cdot a$ , respectively.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] Since the normal forms are literally different, the original terms cannot be equal in every group.
[src:knuth-bendix/word-problem-mathematics] In fact, they are usually different in non-abelian groups.
